John Edward: Knowledge of languages is of great importance for the citizens of the world
Independent schools in Scotland continue the tradition of brilliant education, which was confirmed once again in 2018: outstanding exam results demonstrated individual and collective success in sports, art, music and other socially significant disciplines.
These schools are part of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), where more than 30,000 pupils across Scotland study, and where they strive to provide the highest level of service to pupils and their parents.
Independent schools strive to prepare their students for further higher education, their chosen career, as well as for the status of citizens of the world.
As part of the educational sector, which is responsible for the development and implementation of an individual school curriculum, we see that modern languages continue to be a popular and desirable subject of choice in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you talk to a man in a language he understands, you are appealing to his mind.
If you speak to him in his native language, you are speaking to his heart.”
This is convincing evidence that we cannot rely only on the English language if we want to build relations with citizens of other countries and be able to trust them.
According to the results of the last exams of this year, we see that languages occupy the leading positions in the league tables and have the highest score on the results of exams in independent schools.
A total of 68 per cent of students who studied foreign languages received an “A” grade.
Data from 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72 percent of students received an "A" in Mandarin, while 72 percent of German students, 69 percent of French students, and 63 percent of Spanish students also received an "A."
This proves that in independent schools in Scotland, foreign languages are undoubtedly considered vital for children and young people in the future.
Currently, language subjects are in the same demand as natural sciences, technology, engineering and mathematics in the curricula of independent schools and other educational institutions.
A survey conducted by the UK Employment and Skills Commission in 2014 found that among the reasons that made it difficult for employers to fill vacancies, 17 per cent had a lack of language skills.
Thus, language skills are increasingly becoming the key to a successful future career for young people.
Given that more promising jobs require language skills, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
No matter what profession the student chooses, if he learns a second language, in the future he will gain a real advantage by mastering another additional skill that will be useful to him throughout his life.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically gives a person who knows several foreign languages a competitive advantage.
According to a YouGov poll of more than 4,000 British adults in 2013, 75 percent were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to support the conversation, and French was the only language with a double-digit percentage — 15 percent of respondents say it.
That’s why investing in language education is so important right now.
Knowledge of several languages, especially the languages of developing economies, will give children a better chance of finding a good job.
In schools in Scotland, there is a fairly large variety in terms of languages that are taught - each school has its own set of languages.
A number of schools focus on more classical modern languages, while others teach the languages considered most important to the UK in light of the country’s future development up to 2020 – such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever the interests of your child, independent schools will always have a choice of several languages with a teaching staff whose members are specialists in these languages.
Independent schools in Scotland are committed to creating a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills they need to succeed, no matter what the future holds.
At present, it cannot be denied that, in the global business environment, languages continue to be vital for the country ' s future development, and this should be appropriately reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages really need to be seen as “international communication skills.”
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, providing diversity and benefits to Scotland’s youth.
I'll be honest with you.
John Edwards, Director of the Council of Independent Schools of Scotland
