North Korea says it will not “categorically” disarm unilaterally without confidence
North Korea’s foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that the continued sanctions have increased mistrust of the United States and that his country would under no circumstances give up its nuclear weapons unilaterally.
Ri Yong Ho told the annual General Assembly that North Korea had taken “substantial goodwill measures” last year, such as halting nuclear and missile tests, dismantling a nuclear test site and committing not to build up stockpiles of nuclear weapons or develop nuclear technology.
“However, we do not observe a symmetrical reaction from the United States,” he said.
“Without trust in the United States, there will be no confidence in our national security, and under such circumstances, we will not be able to unilaterally be the first to take action on disarmament.”
While Ri echoed the already-sounding North Korean complaints about Washington’s resistance to a “phased” approach to denuclearization, according to which North Korea would be rewarded for incremental steps, his statement seemed important in the sense that it did not reject unilateral denuclearization without control, as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement made by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first-ever summit between a sitting U.S. president and a North Korean leader, held in Singapore on June 12; then Kim promised to start a movement toward “denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula,” and Trump promised North Korea security guarantees.
North Korea seeks to formally end the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States says Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington is also resisting calls to ease tough international sanctions on North Korea.
“The U.S. insists that ‘denuclearization must be done first,’ and raises the pressure level through sanctions to forcefully achieve its goal, and even objects to the ‘declaration of the end of the war,’” Ree says.
“The notion that sanctions can bring us to our knees is a utopian dream of people who don’t know us.
But the real problem is that continued sanctions reinforce our mistrust.”
Ri made no mention of plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, which the U.S. leader mentioned at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, he focused on three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: “If South Korea, not the United States, were a party to this issue of denuclearization, the denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula would not be at such an impasse.”
However, Ri’s tone was sharply different from last year when he told the UN General Assembly that targeting North Korea’s missiles on the US mainland was inevitable after “Mr. President Evil” Trump called Kim a “suicide bomber.”
At the UN this year, Trump, who last year threatened to “totally destroy” North Korea, praised Kim for his courage in taking disarmament measures, but said there was still much to be done and sanctions should remain in place until North Korea disarmed.
On Wednesday, Trump said he was not setting any timeline for the process: “Whether it takes two years, three years or five months, it doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia believe that the UN Security Council should encourage Pyongyang for the steps that have been taken.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday: “The imposition of sanctions by the Security Council must continue actively and without fail until we see complete, final and verifiable denuclearization.”
The Security Council has unanimously increased sanctions against North Korea since 2006, seeking to cut off funding for Pyongyang’s nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
