Harvard students learn to relax on special courses
The new course, introduced this year at Harvard University, has helped all elementary school students learn to sleep more and combat the chauvinistic culture of continuous caffeine consumption with the goal of staying awake “night after night.”
One academic found that the most successful students in the world often have no idea how to take care of themselves.
Charles Chaisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, has developed a course that he believes is the first of its kind in the US.
After his discovery, he came up with the idea of introducing such a course, having previously made a report on the impact of lack of sleep on learning processes.
“At the end of my talk, a girl came up to me and said, ‘It’s a shame that I only found out about this now that I’m almost out of school.’
She said no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep — which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, first offered to students this year, talks about how the habit of healthy sleep contributes to academic and athletic performance, as well as how it improves a person’s overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the University’s Health Service, says the university has decided to introduce this course after it was found that students experience severe sleep deprivation during the school week.
The lesson lasts one hour, students perform a number of interactive tasks.
In one section of the class, students are shown a room in a dormitory where, by clicking on coffee cups, curtains, exercise machines and books, they are given information about how each of these activities and substances – coffee, light, which cause lack of sleep – affect athletic performance, and how important it is to get enough sleep every day.
In another section, participants will learn about how prolonged sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, stroke, depression, and cancer.
The interactive campus map encourages course participants to reflect on their daily lives.
“We understand that these classes will not change the behavior of students immediately.
