National Trust listens to the secret life of bats
A new study, conducted in one of the estates of the Scottish Highlands, has the task of showing how bats use the landscape in search of food.
It is hoped that the findings will provide a new perspective on the behavior of unique winged mammals and help in further conservation activities.
The study, organized by scientists from the National Fund of Scotland, will examine common bats, soprano bats, as well as brown long-haired bats and night owls of Dobanton, inhabiting Inverewe Gardens, Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be installed at some points around the site to track bat activity throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys using handheld detectors.
Expert sound analysis of all recordings will determine the frequency of screams, as well as the types of activities for which different groups of these animals are responsible.
A habitat map will then be drawn up and a report prepared to create a detailed picture of their behavior on a landscape scale.
Rob Dewar, a conservation adviser at NTS, hopes these results will show which habitats are most important to bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help to identify the main areas of work on the management of the habitat, such as the formation of meadows, as well as ways to maintain forest areas in a state optimal for bats and other related species.
Bat populations in Scotland and across the UK have declined significantly over the last century.
They are threatened with extinction due to construction and development works that affect their habitat and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lighting installations can pose hazards, as can fly duct tape, chemical processing of building materials, and domestic cat hunting.
In reality, bats are not blind.
However, their nocturnal hunting habits are such that their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated echo-location technique to pinpoint obstacles in the flight path.
NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 significant gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, takes bat population issues very seriously.
The organization employs ten trained experts who regularly conduct surveys, on-site inspections, and sometimes rescue work.
The organisation has even set up Scotland’s first and only bat reserve at Threat Manor in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight out of ten Scottish bat species.
Property manager David Thompson says the estate is the perfect territory for them.
“Here, in Threat, it’s a great place for bats,” he says.
“There are old buildings, a lot of old trees and all the elements of a good habitat.
But much about bats remains unknown, so the work we do here and elsewhere will help us better understand what they need to thrive.”
He recalls the importance of checking for bats before carrying out maintenance within private holdings, as the unintentional destruction of one nest can lead to the death of up to 400 females and young individuals, and possibly even the destruction of the entire local population.
Bats are protected by law, their destruction, harassment or destruction of their habitats is illegal.
Elizabeth Ferrell, a Scottish bat conservation officer, calls on the public for help.
She says: “We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and we just don’t know how many of their individual species live.”
