Due to the failure of communications, rescuers can not get any information from Donggal, the area north of Palu, which is closer to the epicenter of the earthquake with a force of 7.5 points.
In Palu, more than 16,000 people were evacuated as a result of the disaster.
Here are some key facts about Palu and Donggala located on Sulawesi Island:
Palu is the capital of Central Sulawesi Province, located at the end of a narrow bay on the west coast of Sulawesi Island, with an estimated population of 379,800 (as of 2017).
The city celebrated its 40th anniversary when an earthquake and tsunami struck.
Donggala is a district stretching along 300 km (180 mi) of coastline in the northwest of Sulawesi Island.
The county, an administrative district smaller than the province, had 299,200 people in 2017.
Fisheries and agriculture are the backbone of the economy of Central Sulawesi Province, and in particular the coastal region of Donggala.
Nickel mining is also important to the province's economy, but is mainly concentrated in Morovali, on the opposite coast of Sulawesi.
According to the Indonesian Disaster Management Agency, the tsunami has devastated Palu and Donggala several times over the past 100 years.
In 1938, a tsunami killed more than 200 people and destroyed hundreds of homes in Donggala.
The tsunami also occurred in western Donggal in 1996, killing nine people.
Indonesia is on the Pacific Volcanic Ring of Fire and regularly suffers from earthquakes.
Here are some of the major earthquakes and tsunamis in recent years:
2004: A strong earthquake on the west coast of the Indonesian province of Aceh in northern Sumatra on 26 December caused a tsunami that hit 14 countries, killing 226,000 people along the Indian Ocean coast, more than half of them in Aceh.
2005: A series of strong earthquakes hit the west coast of Sumatra in late March and early April.
Hundreds of people died on the island of Nias, off the coast of Sumatra.
2006: A 6.8-magnitude earthquake struck south of Java, Indonesia's most populous island, triggering a tsunami that struck the southern coast, killing about 700 people.
2009: An earthquake of magnitude 7.6 occurred in the city of Padang, the capital of West Sumatra province.
More than 1,100 people were killed.
2010: An earthquake with a magnitude of 7.5 occurred on one of the islands of Mentawai near Sumatra, causing a tsunami of up to 10 meters, which destroyed dozens of villages and killed about 300 people.
2016: A weak earthquake struck the Pidi Jaya district of Aceh, causing destruction and panic as people remembered the devastating 2004 earthquake and tsunami.
This time there was no tsunami, but more than 100 people died as a result of the destruction of buildings.
2018: Severe earthquakes hit Indonesia’s tourist island of Lombok, killing more than 500 people, mostly on the north side of the island.
The earthquake destroyed thousands of buildings and thousands of tourists temporarily remained under the ruins.
