Federal prosecutors want to give the suspect in the terrorist attack in New York a rare death sentence
The federal prosecutor’s office in New York is seeking the death penalty for Saifullo Saipov, suspected of carrying out a terrorist attack in New York that killed eight people — a rare punishment for a federal crime that has not been used in the state since 1953.
In October, Saipov, 30, allegedly rented a Home Depot truck to attack a bicycle path on the West Side Highway in Lower Manhattan, knocking down pedestrians and cyclists.
To justify the death sentence, prosecutors will have to prove that Saipov “deliberately” killed eight people and “deliberately” inflicted serious bodily harm, according to a notice of intent to seek the death penalty filed in the Southern District of New York.
According to the court document, these two charges may be sentenced to death.
A few weeks after the attack, a grand federal jury read Saipova a 22-count conviction that included eight counts of racketeering murder commonly used by federal prosecutors in organized crime cases, as well as charges of violence and car destruction.
Prosecutors said the attack was "carefully planned and deliberate", and Saipov carried it out in what they described as "disgusting, cruel and criminal ways".
Saifullo Habibullaevich Saipov caused injury, damage and loss to the families and friends of Diego Enrique Angelini, Nicholas Cleves, Ann-Laura Decadt, Darren Drake, Ariel Erli, Hernan Ferrucci, Hernan Diego Mendoza and Alejandro Damian Pagnuedco.
Five of the dead were tourists from Argentina.
It has been 10 years since a prosecutor in the Southern District of New York sought the death penalty for a criminal offense.
In September 2009, defendant Khalid Barnes was convicted of murdering two drug dealers, but was eventually sentenced to life in prison.
The last time the death penalty in a federal case in New York was applied was in 1953 against Julius and Ethel Rosenberg, a married couple executed for conspiracy to spy for the Soviet Union during the Cold War two years earlier.
The Rosenbergs were executed by electric chair on June 19, 1953.
According to court documents, Saipov, a native of Uzbekistan, showed no remorse after the attack.
According to police, he told investigators that he was glad that he did it.
According to the indictment, Saipov told authorities that he was inspired to commit the attack by watching ISIS videos on his phone.
He also asked to hang the ISIS flag in his hospital ward, police said.
He pleaded not guilty to all 22 counts of the indictment.
David Patton, one of the federal public defenders speaking on Saipov’s side, said they were “clearly disappointed” by the prosecutor’s decision.
“We believe that the decision to use the death penalty rather than life imprisonment without the possibility of release will only exacerbate the pain of these events for all their participants,” Patton said.
Saipov’s defense has previously appealed to prosecutors not to seek the death penalty.
